{"title":"Lotus unveils £20,000 e-road bike with tech from the track, and Mars","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/lotus-e-road-bike","date":1698847200000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/lotus-e-road-bike\">Lotus unveils £20,000 e-road bike with tech from the track, and Mars</a></p>\n\n<p>Lotus has launched an e-road bike called the Type 136. The new design borrows design features from the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/hope-team-gb-track-bike-available-now-starting-at-15550\" target=\"_blank\">Hope-Lotus track bike</a> which was launched in July and saw action at the UCI Glasgow World Championships in August. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Specific details which follow the design of that bike are the very wide stance of the fork legs and the seatstays, and the rise from the head tube to the bars, which results in a lowered top tube. It doesn’t duplicate the track bike’s <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/trek-madone-review\" target=\"_blank\">Trek Madone</a>-like double seatpost design, however.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Claimed lightest e-bike motor system</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"Lotus Type 136 e-bike\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_002_Rear_View_Comp08_TH_FinalArt_LightsOff-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Lotus</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The Type 136 also gets tech from Formula 1 in the form of its <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/10523/best-ebike-systems\" target=\"_blank\">motor system</a> from HPS, which Lotus claims is the lightest electric bike motor available, contributing to a claimed full e-bike weight of 9.8kg, matching or bettering the lightest <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/bikes/e-bikes\" target=\"_blank\">electric road bikes</a> available.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/lotus-110-bike\">In pictures: Lotus’ classic bikes</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/introduction-to-electric-bikes-everything-you-need-to-know\">Introduction to electric bikes: Everything you need to know</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<p>Lotus says that the HPS Watt Assist Pro bottom bracket motor weighs 300g and uses tech from the Mars Lander, where reliable, zero-maintenance running and low weight are obviously essential.  </p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"650\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-970x650.jpg\" alt=\"Lotus Type 136 e-bike\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-970x650.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-300x201.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-768x515.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-1536x1030.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-2048x1373.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-750x503.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/sh06001_014_Bidon_Comp02_RBN_FinalArt_Lotus-1140x764.jpg 1140w\" /><figcaption>Charlotte Head</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s powered by a removable bottle-style battery on the seat tube, similar to the range extender batteries available for Mahle eBikemotion and Specialized motor systems, rather than the in-frame batteries more normal on performance e-road bikes. Lotus claims that the complete system weighs just 1.2kg.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>HPS also sells its own range of electric road bikes which use its motor system. It offers an 85Wh battery which it claims weighs 720g and a 193Wh battery with a claimed 1.2kg weight. Lotus doesn’t say which comes as standard with the Type 136, but we’d guess the former. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Other details about the system, including its power and torque numbers and potential range, are scant, both from Lotus itself and from Monaco-based HPS.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>New road bike trends?</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"648\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-970x648.jpg\" alt=\"Lotus Type 136 e-bike\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-970x648.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-768x513.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-1536x1026.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-2048x1368.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-750x501.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-1140x761.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/11/2023_07_017_Lotus_DAY_02_3915_Comp04_TH_FinalArt_Lotus-copy-2-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Lotus</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The V-shaped rising handlebars are reminiscent of those of the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/reviews/cervelo-s5-review-2\" target=\"_blank\">Cervélo S5</a> and the Bianchi Oltre road race bikes, as well as the Hope-Lotus track bike. And although the wide fork stance flows directly from the track bike, it’s another feature that’s appearing elsewhere, most notably on the new <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/bmc-teammachine-r-2024\" target=\"_blank\">BMC Teammachine R</a> road bike and the BMC Speedmachine time-trial bike.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>At the launch of the Type 136 at the Lotus brand store in London, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/chris-hoy-knight-rider\" target=\"_blank\">Sir Chris Hoy</a>, now a Lotus ambassador, commented: ‘This is an incredible bike, which says so much about the pioneering endeavours of Lotus and the iconic status of its bikes over the years. As a teenager I vividly remember watching Chris Boardman powering the Type 108 to a gold medal in Barcelona in 1992 and smashing records on the Type 110 to wear the yellow jersey in the Tour de France two years later.’</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Price and availability</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The Lotus Type 136 will be sold in a limited first edition of just 136 bikes, which are individually numbered and painted in a colour scheme which Lotus says is motorsport-inspired. The pricetag? £20,000 / €25,000. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The Lotus Type 136 e-bike will be on display at the Rouleur Live show in London from tomorrow and there are more details on <a href=\"https://www.lotuscars.com/en-GB/type-136\" target=\"_blank\">Lotus’s site</a>. The standard model will be available from Spring 2024.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Read more about the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/hope-lotus-track-bike-team-gb-2023\" target=\"_blank\">Hope-Lotus Team GB track bike</a> for the Paris Olympics. </em></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/lotus-e-road-bike\">Lotus unveils £20,000 e-road bike with tech from the track, and Mars</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"pnorman","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"29b3500ef2701a027dd93e3b53d702e5ccc08e2a05d7102a1bfab639e07dc0e6","category":"Cycling"}